Source: Florida Department of Health, press release, Mon 20 Aug 2001 [edited
<http://www.doh.state.fl.us/disease_ctrl/epi/htopics/arbo/press_releases.htm>

Florida's third human case of West Nile virus encephalitis reported
-------------------------------------------------------------------
TALLAHASSEE: The Florida Department of Health announced today that a third
human case of encephalitis caused by the West Nile (WN) virus has been
diagnosed. The case is a 40 year old man from Jefferson County. There have
been 2 [other? - Mod.SH confirmed human cases of WN virus encephalitis and
2 confirmed cases of Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) in Florida.
Jefferson County is already under a medical alert issued by health
officials for EEE and West Nile virus. The alert is now in effect for 30
north Florida counties, including: Baker, Bay, Bradford, Calhoun, Clay,
Columbia, Duval, Escambia, Franklin, Gadsden, Gulf, Hamilton, Holmes,
Jackson, Jefferson, Lafayette, Leon, Levy, Liberty, Madison, Nassau,
Okaloosa, Santa Rosa, St. Johns, Suwannee, Taylor, Union, Wakulla, Walton,
and Washington counties.
For more information on mosquito borne encephalitis, including reporting
human cases and dead birds, visit the Florida Department of Health Bureau
of Epidemiology's Arboviral Encephalitis and West Nile Virus website
<http://www.doh.state.fl.us/disease_ctrl/epi/htopics/arbo/index.htm>.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A total of 5 cases of human West Nile virus infection have been confirmed
in the USA for the year 2001 so far. In addition to the 3 cases in Florida,
one case has been reported in New York (Staten Island) and one in Georgia.
The patient in Georgia has died, with death attributed to the effects of
West Nile virus infection. - Mod.CP
